# Walkthrough: Inner Surface Reconstruction (Step 1)

## What was built

Created [extract_surface.py](file:///home/mi3dr/Endo-4DGS/extract_surface.py) — a pipeline that extracts a 3D mesh from a trained Endo-4DGS model using TSDF volume fusion.

### Pipeline steps
1. **Load** trained model + dataset cameras
2. **Render** depth maps from all training views (using the Gaussian renderer)
3. **Mask** out surgical tools (using the tool masks from training)
4. **Fuse** all depth frames into a TSDF volume via Open3D
5. **Extract** watertight triangle mesh via marching cubes
6. **Export** camera trajectory as JSON (positions + orientations per frame)

## Test Results

| Model | Views | Vertices | Triangles | Mesh Size | Time |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **pulling** | 55 | 75,744 | 147,792 | 5.6 MB | ~15s |
| **cutting** | 136 | 94,999 | 185,422 | ~7 MB | ~45s |

### Output files
```
output/endonerf/pulling/surface_reconstruction/iteration_3000/
├── fused_mesh.ply           # Watertight triangle mesh
├── fused_pointcloud.ply     # Colored point cloud
└── camera_trajectory.json   # Per-frame camera poses (c2w, w2c, position, forward)
```

## Usage

```bash
# Basic usage
python extract_surface.py --model_path output/endonerf/pulling --configs arguments/endonerf.py

# Finer mesh (more memory)
python extract_surface.py --model_path output/endonerf/pulling --configs arguments/endonerf.py --voxel_size 0.3

# Include tools in reconstruction
python extract_surface.py --model_path output/endonerf/pulling --configs arguments/endonerf.py --no_mask
```

